Along the Way

Dara talks as you walk. She doesn't boast; she inventories. Oskar built the storehouse frame, mortise-and-tenon joints, no nails. Maren figured out the clay lining for the rain cistern so the water doesn't taste of wood. Fen keeps the watch rotation fair, three shifts, nobody pulls doubles unless they volunteer.

She mentions the other camps in the forest. Code names. Dead drops. People who've lived within shouting distance for years and never learned each other's faces. She doesn't judge them for it. She understands the logic. Out here, anyone who knows your name can sell it. Anyone who knows where you sleep can lead someone to you. Trust is currency, and most exiles are broke.

"We decided to be poor together," she says. "That was the whole idea. Stop hoarding secrets and start building something." She shifts the grain sacks on her shoulders. The chicken has fallen asleep. "It worked. I know it sounds like it shouldn't, but it worked."

The trail dips through a stand of birch and the light goes gold and then green. Dara is already talking about the new seedlings, what to plant where, which beds get morning sun.

choices:

* Continue to the Commons
  The trail opens ahead. Dara quickens her pace.
